---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Binary World"
  description="Splitting as a compression algorithm — when the system cannot hold contradiction, the world becomes black and white."
>
  <article class="piece-page">
    <a href="/artwork/" class="back">← Artwork</a>

    <div class="piece-image">
      <img
        src="/artwork/creation-of-adam.png"
        alt="Two hands reaching toward each other in black and white — a silhouette reinterpretation of Michelangelo's Creation of Adam, representing the gap between externalized regulation and connection"
      />
    </div>

    <div class="piece-text">
      <h1>The Binary World</h1>
      <p class="piece-subtitle">Splitting as a Compression Algorithm</p>

      <h2>What this image shows</h2>
      <p>
        Two hands reaching toward each other across a gap — rendered entirely
        in black and white. A reinterpretation of Michelangelo's Creation of Adam
        as a regulation metaphor. The reaching is not creation here. It is the
        moment before contact — the space where connection is sought but not yet
        achieved. The gap between needing and receiving.
      </p>

      <h2>The reaching as externalization</h2>
      <p>
        In the original fresco, God reaches toward Adam — giving life, giving
        form. In this version, the reaching is ambiguous. Who is giving and who
        is receiving? Is this co-regulation or dependence? Is the gap about to
        close — or is it permanent?
      </p>
      <p>
        The image captures the fundamental tension of external regulation:
        the hand that reaches outward is seeking something it cannot generate
        internally. Stability, coherence, identity confirmation — something
        that requires another hand to complete.
      </p>

      <h2>The binary rendering</h2>
      <p>
        The black and white treatment removes nuance from the scene. There is
        no gradient, no ambiguity in the rendering itself — only presence and
        absence, figure and void. This visual compression mirrors the psychological
        mechanism of splitting:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The other is either reaching back (all good, safe, available)</li>
        <li>Or the other is withdrawing (all bad, rejecting, absent)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        No middle ground. No "reaching back imperfectly." No "available but
        distracted." The binary image cannot represent partial availability —
        just as the splitting system cannot hold partial goodness.
      </p>

      <h2>The gap as structural truth</h2>
      <p>
        The space between the hands is not empty. It contains everything the
        system cannot hold internally: uncertainty about whether contact will
        happen, tolerance of the other's separateness, acceptance that reaching
        does not guarantee receiving.
      </p>
      <p>
        In SRF terms: the gap is where IRC lives. The capacity to remain
        coherent while the hand is extended but not yet met. The capacity to
        tolerate the interval — the REL — between reaching and receiving.
      </p>

      <div class="component">
        <h3>Idealization</h3>
        <p>The other hand will always reach back. The gap will always close. Contact is guaranteed. All white — the object is entirely safe, entirely available.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="component">
        <h3>Devaluation</h3>
        <p>The other hand will never reach back. The gap is permanent. Contact is impossible. All black — the object is entirely rejecting, entirely absent.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="component">
        <h3>Integration</h3>
        <p>The other hand may or may not reach back — and I can survive either outcome. The gap exists. I can hold it. Grey emerges: partial availability, imperfect connection, good enough.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>The structural interpretation</h2>
      <p class="insight">
        The reaching hand is not weakness. It is what regulation looks like
        when it cannot remain fully internal. The question is not whether we
        reach — all humans reach. The question is: what happens to the system
        when the other hand is not there? Does it collapse into black, flee
        into white — or can it hold the grey of the gap itself?
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .piece-page {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 1rem 0 4rem;
  }

  .back {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .back:hover { color: var(--text); }

  .piece-image {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #000;
  }
  .piece-image img { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }

  h1 { margin: 0 0 0.25rem; font-size: 2rem; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
  .piece-subtitle { margin: 0 0 2rem; font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--muted); font-style: italic; }
  h2 { margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem; font-size: 1.2rem; }
  h3 { margin: 0 0 0.4rem; font-size: 1rem; color: var(--accent); }
  p { line-height: 1.75; color: var(--muted); }

  ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
  }
  li { margin-bottom: 0.3rem; }

  .component {
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background: var(--surface);
  }
  .component p { margin: 0; }

  .insight {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--surface);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }
</style>
